<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceratophyllum demersum</i> is an aquatic plant with brittle, whorled, forked leaves on stems that are generally 1 to 3 meters long. It can form a dense subsurface canopy in still or slow-moving water. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ceratophyllum demersum</i> occurs throughout much of California, with the exceptions of the desert mountains, White and Inyo mountains, Channel Islands, Tehachapi Mountains, and Cascade Range foothills. Stands are found in water that is fresh to brackish and usually alkaline, with medium to high nutrient levels (Les 2017). Despite its widespread distribution in California, few samples have been collected.<br/>
<br/>
This Provisional Alliance is a name reassignment from the <i>Potamogeton</i> spp. - <i>Ceratophyllum</i> spp. - <i>Elodea</i> spp. Provisional Alliance in Buck et al. (2012). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> In natural areas, <i>Ceratophyllum demersum</i> is a desirable component of aquatic habitats, providing food and shelter for wildlife. However, mats can inhibit water flow, block intake screens of water pumps, and interfere with recreational activities (DiTomaso et al. 2013).

High nutrient conditions favored by this alliance may be enhanced by enriched runoff in agricultural or urban landscapes (NatureServe 2015). <i>C. demersum</i> has been spread throughout the world through the aquarium and pond trade and is considered a weed in many places, where it can dominate waterways (IUCN Species Survival Commission 2017).

The alliance has a worldwide distribution in low gradient streams and eutrophic ponds and small lakes. It is assumed widely distributed in California in these habitats, based on known observations of the species in almost all ecological sections of the state; but further study and observations would be beneficial. The alliance was first described in the Great Valley (M262A; Buck-Diaz et al. 2012), based on a survey done near San Luis Island. Stands also likely occur in all subsections with small fresh water bodies within the Great Valley. Stands are known from the Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B) in Sonoma County (Klein et al. 2015). Currently, a <i>Ceratophyllum demersum </i>association [1], [2] is recognized. </div>
</div>

	

    
